After asking you all what my next post should be, the most requested was a “bad book review”. Here you go! All my thoughts on Educated. 

I first read Educated years ago with my book club while living in North Carolina. This is when I was a newish reader and was excited to read a memoir. I had issues from the start with Educated, mainly because from what I was hearing, people were comparing Educated with The Glass Castle, which easily is one of my favorite books of all time.

Years later, my thoughts on Educated have not changed (regardless of your attempt to persuade me). Not only did I think Educated was poorly written, the storyline was so elaborated and difficult to digest. I had zero interest in reading a prematurely thought out memoir of someone who is clearly still in the thick of their family drama and troubles. One of the things that I found so insightful about The Glass Castle was the introspective outlook and full circle story. It felt relatable in a sense that families are not perfect, but maybe it is possible to have closure and perspective and understanding about the people who are closest to us.

Memoirs are tricky because I don’t want to discredit someones “story,” but I found Tara’s childhood stories far-fetched. Maybe those trauma moments left an impression and cemented those memories, but everything seemed difficult to believe. I’m not a psychoanalyist but that’s just my opinion. She clearly has a lot of confidence in herself and her abilities, but maybe do a google search of Tara singing…spoiler: it isn’t good. 

Obviously, this is one of my hot button bad books that I’ve read and manyyyyy of you have sent me DMs over the years wanting to know my opinion on Educated. Well- Merry Christmas. This is my gift to you. 🙃

What can I say that hasn’t already been said about this incredible book? I’m kicking myself for taking this long picking up an Amy Harmon book (I’m so sorry it took me this long @amy.harmon.author ) and now I’ve stacked my TBR with all her backlist titles for the next little while.

Where the Lost Wander is primarily about the May family traveling across the Overland Trail in 1853, but there is so much in this story that captured my heart. 

The development and detail of every character was so rich, but the character that I loved the most was John Lowry. John was the guide for the May family, but we learn bits and pieces about John and his upbringing throughout the beginning of the story. We learn about the relationships between the Indian tribes and their people. 

There is a lot of tragedy along this treacherous trail but the people crossing were so courageous and determined to make a better life for their families. I have always admired the strength of the early settlers. My own family has history of crossing the plains and settling in Canada and this gave me a bit of insight into the difficult road they chose and the many things and comforts they sacrificed in order to create a better life. 

One of the pieces of this story that caught me off guard was how connected I would feel to the Indian tribes and their beautiful traditions. John Lowry was the bridge to connect both worlds and I found Harmon’s writing to be so beautiful and respectful as she approached these conflicts. History is difficult to understand at times, but there is always something to be learned and I learned so much.

Wow! This story is going to stick with me for awhile! All the stars!

Let’s talk about being honest with our book reviews and ratings.

Something I really want to work on this year is making sure my book reviews are honest and reflect how I actually felt about the book while reading. So often my default rating is ⭐️⭐️⭐️ for a book that I really didn’t enjoy reading but I may feel bad giving it a lower rating or wonder if it was more of a me problem than a book problem. Does that make sense? I honestly hate sitting on that ⭐️⭐️⭐️ fence. Maybe what a ⭐️⭐️⭐️ rating is saying is that while it may not have worked for me, it may work for you. But ⭐️⭐️ is my way of saying don’t waste time on this one. Capiche?

For example, Before I Do was a total flop for me. Storyline, pacing, characters…it bored me to death. When I finished, my knee jerk reaction was ⭐️⭐️⭐️. Why??? I hated it. I didn’t enjoy it. I was bored. I didn’t like anyone in the book (except Josh-dude, you deserve better!). I sat on that feeling for a few minutes and decided to drop it to ⭐️⭐️. Yes- it shocked bookstagram, but I felt like it was an honest reflection on my reading experience. 

So here’s to making sure that we are being true to ourselves with how we really feel about a book and not worry about offending everyone.

February’s MBC book pick is…

Someday, Maybe by Onyi Nwabineli 🧡🧡🧡 

As you know, I read Someday, Maybe a few months ago and was an instant 5 ⭐️ read for me. This story has had a hold on my heart ever since and I desperately want you to get to know the main character, Eve. Her story of grief was so palpable and real, I couldn’t believe that this was the authors debut book. How was this not a nonfiction story??

One of the reasons why I chose this book was for the simple fact that as humans, we need to increase our ability to grieve with those that grieve. We need to learn how to sit in those uncomfortable places and support whoever is grieving in our lives. Someday, Maybe will give us those opportunities and put us in those uncomfortable feelings. I haven’t been able to stop thinking about this story and I hope you join me this month.

As for the story, this very Knives Out kind of family drama had me at the edge of my seat. Obviously, the title grabbed my attention instantly. How could it not? And while there were some gory parts (yes people do get killed in this book), there is way more plot development happening with twists and turns on every page. This audiobook demanded my focus 100%, which hasn’t happened in a long time! I had to go back and listen to the last 30 minutes to process through the “reveals” one more time. It was clever and very well done. 

I’m not sure what is holding me back from 5 glowing stars, but it was a great audiobook. And I can’t wait for book 2 coming this fall.

Synopsis:
Paris, 1939: Young mothers Elise and Juliette become fast friends the day they meet in the beautiful Bois de Boulogne. Though there is a shadow of war creeping across Europe, neither woman suspects that their lives are about to irrevocably change.

When Elise becomes a target of the German occupation, she entrusts Juliette with the most precious thing in her life—her young daughter, playmate to Juliette’s own little girl. But nowhere is safe in war, not even a quiet little bookshop like Juliette’s Librairie des Rêves, and, when a bomb falls on their neighborhood, Juliette’s world is destroyed along with it.

More than a year later, with the war finally ending, Elise returns to reunite with her daughter, only to find her friend’s bookstore reduced to rubble—and Juliette nowhere to be found. What happened to her daughter in those last, terrible moments? Juliette has seemingly vanished without a trace, taking all the answers with her. Elise’s desperate search leads her to New York—and to Juliette—one final, fateful time.

It isn’t too often that I come across a historical fiction story that completely sweets me up and captures my heart in all the best ways! The Paris Daughter hit all the high notes for me and I’m so excited for you to read along with me.

I owe a lot The Silent Patient. It was one of those early books that really got me hooked on reading. I wasn’t always a reader. In fact, my reading ability was always behind my grade level. You’d think I would conclude that reading more might solve my problem, but no, it didn’t click for me. 

After I had my third baby, I met a few women that always talked about the latest book they were reading and it was like a lightbulb went off in my mind. It was decided: the next time I took my little kids to the library, I would grab a few books for myself. 

Well, those 2-3 books a year turned into 5-8 books a month, and now 8 years later, I’m averaging 100 books a year! 

I guess what I’m saying is that being a reader can start at any time! I hope my sharing has helped you either begin or rediscover a love of reading too. ❤️ 

Did reading come early to you or later in your life like me? I’d love to hear!

Recipe:
 Peach Cobbler

5 peaches, peeled, cored, and sliced (about 4 cups)
3/4 cup granulated sugar
1/4 tsp salt

For the batter:
6 tbsp butter
1 cup all-purpose flour
1 cup granulated sugar
2 tsp baking powder
1/4 tsp salt
3/4 cup milk
Ground cinnamon

1. Add the sliced peaches, sugar, and salt in a saucepan and warm through for 2-3 minutes to bring out the peach juices.
2. Preheat oven to 350 and slice up the butter and add to a 9x13 baking dish. Plan pan in oven and allow the butter to melt. Once melted, take out of oven.
3. Mix up the batter. Pour the mixture over the melted butter and add peaches over top. Sprinkle cinnamon. Bake at 350 for 40 minutes!

In my opinion, the perfect book club is full of disagreements and opinions. People speaking passionately about why the book did or did not work for them. I’m on a quest to find clean YA novels for the 13-17 aged boys and girls and let me tell you, it has been very eye opening so far! 

The thing is, as a parent, you’re gonna have your own content threshold with your child. My content red flags for my 14 yo might will look different to your red flags. My daughter is an advanced reader and has been staying in the same middle grade genre for years because the YA genre is not as controlled with their content. 

YA authors (some not all) seem to be writing in this genre with adults being their demographic of readers. While that is true that adults are reading YA, it isn’t easy as a parent to hand over any book in this genre and think it will be appropriate for their under 18 yo child. Language, sex, coming of age, and heavy topics are explored in this genre and I’m trying to find the books that are worth giving to my daughter. 

➡️ CHECK & MATE is a YA debut and the perfect example of a book that is presented as YA, but is clearly adult fiction. It has strong adult themes, language, and sex scenes. The main characters are 19/20 yo which is normal for that type of behavior to happen, but when the YA genre starts at 13 yo….I don’t believe that content is appropriate for that age group. There were sooooo many other issues with CHECK & MATE, I cannot recommend this one to adults either.

I’m finished with Tom Lake and I’m undecided how I feel about it. 

You know I’m an audiobook girl, but I really struggled with Meryl’s narration. On the one hand, I could picture her like as if it was a movie. I could see her talking with her three grown daughters and remembering this short moment in her life and the events after, while also withholding memories that didn’t need to be shared. I could seeeeee it all. 

But- her narration wasn’t good. Her voices weren’t developed. It came off as over dramatic at times. And one of the daughter’s voices was so cringe to listen to. I had her at 2.0 speed and didn’t sweat a bit trying to follow along with the story.

I’m not rushing to rate this one. Let me marinate for a few days and then I’ll decide. I know this for sure, Ann’s writing is immersive, character-driven, and very very well written. Her small snapshot in someone’s lives doesn’t necessarily provide us with a story necessarily, but her books catch us by surprise with feeling a lot and causing us to pause. I can appreciate that. 

So for now, let me leave you with this suggestion to skip the audio and pick up the physical book.
